<section id="faq">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-label"><span class="idx">05 -</span> Honest questions</div>
    <h2 class="heading">Answers, in the order people ask.</h2>

    <div class="faq">
      <details class="qa" open>
        <summary>Is this just another hosting platform? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="answer">
          Not quite. Porvi is opinionated about one thing - Astro static sites with custom
          domains, for individuals and small groups. If you need serverless functions,
          container workloads, or a database, there are much better tools. We do the narrow
          thing well.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="qa">
        <summary>Why invite-only? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="answer">
          Because it's run out of love, not growth. Keeping the circle small means every site
          gets attention, every build is fast, and nothing is oversubscribed. Invites open
          occasionally; leave your email and we'll reach out.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="qa">
        <summary>Do you only support Astro? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="answer">
          For now, yes. Astro's static output and content collections map cleanly onto how
          Porvi thinks about sites. Other frameworks may follow; none are planned as of
          this writing.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="qa">
        <summary>What about custom domains - any catch? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="answer">
          None. Point a CNAME (or A record for apex) and we handle the certificate. Your
          domain stays yours; we never rewrite it, and we never route through a subdomain of
          ours in production.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="qa">
        <summary>How do I get my stuff out? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="answer">
          It never stopped being yours. Your repository lives with you (GitHub, Codeberg,
          self-hosted), and your deploys are just static bundles you can mirror anywhere.
          Porvi is the glue, not the landlord.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
